Detailed Description

An gaia::core::Instrumentation that runs various types of gtest::TestCases against an Gaia package (application).

Typical usage:

  1. Write gtest::TestCases that perform unit, functional, or performance tests against the classes in your package. Typically these are subclassed from:
    • gaia::testing::PageInstrumentationTestCase
    • gaia::testing::PageUnitTestCase
    • gaia::testing::GaiaTestCase
    • gaia::testing::InstrumentationTestCase
    • gaia::testing::DelegateTestCase
    • gaia::testing::SingleLaunchPageTestCase
  2. In an appropriate gaia.xml, define the this instrumentation with the appropriate gaia:targetPackage set.
  3. Run the instrumentation using "adb shell tas instrument <package name> <TestRunner class name> [[gtest-option] [gtest-option] ...]".

Running all tests: adb shell instrument com.example.testframeworktest.test gaia::testing::InstrumentationTestRunner

Running tests with gtest options: adb shell tas instrument com.example.testframeworktest.test gaia::testing::InstrumentationTestRunner --gtest_filter=PageUITestCase.* --gtest_repeat=2

void gaia::testing::InstrumentationTestRunner::onCreate ( gaia::core::Persistence *  arguments) [virtual]

Called when the Instrumentation is starting, before any application code has been loaded.

Usually this will be implemented to simply start the Instrumentation thread, which will then continue execution in onStart.

If you do not need your own thread -- that is you are writing your Instrumentation to be completely asynchronous (returning to the event loop so that the application can run), you can simply begin your Instrumentation here, for example call Context#startPage to begin the appropriate first page of the application.

Parameters:
argumentsAny additional arguments that were supplied when the instrumentation was started.

Reimplemented from gaia::core::Instrumentation.

void gaia::testing::InstrumentationTestRunner::onStart ( ) [virtual]

Method where the instrumentation thread enters execution.

This allows you to run your instrumentation code in a separate thread than the application, so that it can perform blocking operation such as sendKeySync or startPageSync.

You will typically want to call finish() when this function is done, to end your instrumentation.
